      "body": "Understood. You guys are right. However, I wonder if it applies here. While computing the inverse of a privatekey is a low-level operation, I suspect it's only done in contexts in which it's a required operation that would be implemented anyway (i.e. it's not subverting otherwise high-level functionality).\r\n\r\nI notice it's also implemented by quite a few EC libraries and bindings as well, so I suspect if this library exposes it, it'll only be less likely to implemented badly. \r\n\r\nIn my case, it's a required operation of a blinded signature scheme I am working with. I don't really have the luxury of avoiding it, it's just a question of if I can use libsecp256k1 already efficient implementation or my own slow crappy version. \r\n\r\nAlso is it much different than something like `secp256k1_ec_privkey_negate` ?",
